<P><B>Show Me the C++</B><BR/>
<I>At TopCoder.com, programmers battle it out for the chance to prove their worth to potential employers.</I></P>

<P>
So you think you can code? Rob Hughes wants you to prove it. Twice a week, Hughes stages all-out online brawls for hundreds of engineers at TopCoder.com. Sign in for a round and you're presented three mind-bending problems, an hour and 15 minutes to work, and a virtual roomful of competitors eager to find creative ways to prove you wrong.
</P>

<P>
The result? Think of it as <i>Iron Chef</i> for the pocket-protector crowd. To Hughes, the site's co-founder, it's also an investment. He doles out coveted rankings and prize money (as much as $300 for the winner of each match), and in return he receives one of the richer databases of programming talent ever assembled. 
</P>

<P>
The idea is to get blue-chip technology companies to sponsor the contests and, ultimately, to help the programmers get jobs. Hughes also hopes to farm out software projects to the TopCoder elite. So far, TopCoder has drummed up a few hundred thousand dollars in sponsorship money from the likes of <a href="http://www.business2.com/webguide/0,1660,22013,00.html" class="bodyText">Sun Microsystems</a> (<a href="http://qs.money.cnn.com/apps/stockquote?symbols=SUNW" class="bodyText">SUNW</a>) and <a href="http://www.business2.com/webguide/0,1660,6775,00.html" class="bodyText" target="_blank">Motorola</a> (<a href="http://qs.money.cnn.com/apps/stockquote?symbols=MOT" class="bodyText" target="_blank">MOT</a>), and the contests are drawing software whizzes (such as Reid Barton, considered the Michael Jordan of Java) from around the world. And Hughes and his brother Jack, co-founder of the site, do have a track record as entrepreneurs: In 2000, they sold their software startup, Tallan, to <a href="http://www.business2.com/webguide/0,1660,70995,00.html" class="bodyText">CMGI</a> (<a href="http://qs.money.cnn.com/apps/stockquote?symbols=CMGI" class="bodyText">CMGI</a>) for $920 million in stock and cash.
</P>

<P>
The best thing about TopCoder, contestants say, is that it helps separate wannabes from true developers. "I've seen people who could talk but couldn't code, and if you're writing code, talk is no help," says Sergey Kalinichenko, a programmer at San Francisco's Tenfold and an occasional TopCoder combatant. And, by injecting competitive zeal into one of the most mundane tasks on earth, the site is turning computer programming into something ... well, if not interesting, at least a lot less boring. "I can't play basketball," Kalinichenko says, "so programming is pretty much the only thing a nerd like me can compete in."
</P>
